AUDIO: 'Big AI video updates today. We\'ve got a new video model, Happy Horse from Alibaba. Touted by some as a SeaDance killer, I\'m just going to say off the top, it is not, but this pony does have a pretty interesting tail. Plus, Topaz'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'has released a pretty substantial update to their video upscaler. I\'ll say it might be the best I\'ve seen yet. And did you know Kling can do 4K now? Wait.'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Are we in 4K right now? We are. Do you feel bigger? But don\'t you upload in 1080? Boy, she is nothing but snark and attitude since she became a movie star.'

[00:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Also, Netflix have released a new open-source video model. File that under words I never expected to say, but it does look super useful. All right, on that note, ta-da! Kicking off, Happy Horse, the new video'

[00:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model from Alibaba, is here. Uh, and it\'s been a pretty interesting road to release. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Why the long face?'

[01:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This one initially caught everyone\'s attention when it was released on the arenas and quickly shot up to the, well, number one and number two positions on the AI video leaderboards with text to video and image to video. At times, it'

[01:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was actually unseating SeaDance. Again, I will say, temper your expectations here, but on that front, the interesting part of this story is the who of Happy Horse. Well, that is Zhang Di, who up'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'until recently was the VP at Kuaishou, where he was the architect behind Kling 1.0 and 2.0. So, yeah, that is Daddy Kling. Uh, Zhang left Kuaishou in the'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fall of 2025. He joined Alibaba in November, and now, well, like 5 months later, has shipped a brand new model. I mean, that is pretty baller. That out of the way, let\'s go dive into Happy Horse.'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Overall, I\'m going to say it very much does have a V1 vibe to it, uh, but let\'s kick it off with a text to video test of our man in a blue business suit running away from a jaywalking ticket. Overall, I mean, it\'s pretty good. There'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are some problems here and there, like spatial awareness, like the cops just kind of appear in the background there. They did not appear in the establishing shot. And as you can see in the beginning, like our guy kind of manages to force push the cab a little bit. So,'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some physics stuff there, but I think the run cycle actually looks pretty good here. One thing I do want to note, and a discovery that I made later into my testing, is that Happy Horse really wants brevity in its prompt. So, earlier'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'attempts with like the longer prompt format, the kind that we use in SeaDance, yielded results like this, which, you know, there\'s there\'s stuff that definitely works in here, but clearly there\'s a lot of, again, like'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'spatial problems here. This was pointed out by the gang over at Fall. I mean, you can do things like shot lists with time codes and, you know, markdowns in subject, action, settings, camera, lighting, etc.'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But, also, you know, kind of keep your token keyword spamming down to a minimum. Uh, and then, you know, of course, the standard default prompting of like subject does action in setting, time of day, atmosphere, or camera. Um,'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yeah, I mean, just this is a model that does not want you to give it, uh, 3,000 characters written by ChatGPT or Claude. This This kind of feels like one that actually wants you to type. And I\'m not'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'necessarily mad about that, but I mean, this is something definitely to know is that this is a horse that runs a lot better when you loosen the reins. On the image to video side, I figured we kick it off with one of the channel'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'standards, the Twin Peaks-inspired FBI agent drinking coffee in a diner. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; This is a damn fine cup of Joe. But how\'s the pie?'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s really good. It\'s an old recipe from the Log Lady, who got it from the owls. Overall, I mean, I have to say that there is some good and some bad in here. The bad, I'

[04:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mean, I think you very immediately queued in on in that the voices do sound very like stilted and robotic. I\'m sure that that\'s something that they\'ll sort of patch out at some point or another. Um, the other thing I noticed is in the'

[04:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'beginning segments, you\'ll notice that like it almost takes a minute for the lip sync to catch up. So, sometimes you\'ll catch some dialogue before the character actually starts moving their mouth. I\'ve seen this repeatedly. That said, once it does get going, uh, the'

[04:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lip sync does seem to be rock solid. Now, I do want to point out that Happy Horse is actually pretty good in terms of prompt adherence. Our waitress in the background has her back to camera. She turns around, delivers the pie. And'

[04:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'again, in the initial image, there she has no face. So, Happy Horse has to generate one up for her, and it does a pretty solid job. Now, if you were wondering about your SeaDance style kung fu fight scenes, this is definitely not'

[05:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the model for that. At least right now it isn\'t. So, yeah, I mean, it makes an attempt, but, yeah, this is definitely again, not its strong suit. This is not to say that it can\'t do action and won\'t surprise you. Taking this image and'

[05:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'giving it the prompt of a tracking shot of the man slowly walking towards the truck, a thug hops out of the car holding a shotgun. He takes a shot, and the man dodges. We ended up with this.'

[05:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I mean, guy, you were supposed to dodge. This one\'s on you. Now, I do want to'

[05:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'note that there is no first frame, last frame currently. I do know that they\'re working on that, but for now it is just first frame only. Additionally, things that they\'re working on, the aspect ratios available are only, uh, 9 by 16'

[05:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up to 16 by 9, so no 2:1 just quite yet. We do have 1080, which is nice. Generations will go up to 15 seconds. And then, if you\'re on the Happy Horse, uh, website, uh, you can generate up to'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'four generations at a time. Now, we do have a reference mode or omni mode, essentially. I\'ve I\'ve really been enjoying these lately. Uh, this one takes up to nine images. Again, as always, it can get a little bit on the'

[06:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tricky side. So, uh, let\'s first take a look at one that worked. Tom! It\'s good to see you. Is Planet Hell 2 coming out soon? Yeah, yeah. I think Tim is still working on it.'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'What about you? Uh, yeah. My movie came out already. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; So, an issue that I was running into with previous generations here is that, if you\'ll note, in this first like Tom'

[06:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually walks past in the second version. I think Tom walks past on this side. Yeah, there he goes there. And then in this version, yeah, Tom is just kind of walking around in the background. I think the reason that this'

[06:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was happening is that, in the prompt I called out for on a New York street, image one sees image two. So, yeah, that essentially calls out immediately for both characters to appear in that'

[07:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'opening frame. So, just as an overall note, if something\'s not working, go back and check your prompts. I don\'t think that there\'s like a prompt editor that\'s happening, uh, on Happy Horse. But, I will say, when your prompt is pretty tuned up, the reference model can'

[07:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do some pretty good stuff. Um, for example, taking our typical Malloy Detective Office, Tuesday Sinclair entering to hire a detective, except this time it\'s Renfield the pirate. Mr. Renfield, I hear you\'re a pirate.'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] And I am in need of one. You are I be a pirate. What be the case? So, yeah. Well, obviously, you know, the voice does not match, but it also kind of works for me.'

[07:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In terms of video performance, I think that the reference model does a very good job here. In particular, no pushback on Renfield as I commonly get on a number of other video generators. So, yeah, overall, is Happy Horse a'

[07:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'SeaDance killer? No, it is not. But, that doesn\'t mean it\'s a bad model. It\'s just kind of early in, and, you know, considering that the Happy Horse team got this up and running in about 5 months, it does lead me to believe that'

[08:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'given some updates and a little more time, this could be a contender. So, yeah, I mean, this is a horse to watch. Moving on, the Topaz gang has been cooking. I mean, they have obviously long been considered the industry'

[08:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'standard for video upscaling, and took a big jump into AI video with the release of their Astra and Starlight models. One of the complaints about the version one model is that it tended to have, you know, kind of a heavy hand at times,'

[08:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and really kind of like smooth things out a bit too much. In particular, you\'ll notice here, like, it actually takes away our girl\'s moles. Here, you know, and just, you know, smooths everything out just a little too much. I'

[08:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'am happy to report that is not the case with the 2.5 model. I\'m just going to run This is a SeaDance output. I\'m just going to kind of scroll the wiper as we play it. You\'re late.'

